{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S3UPzU7DE9rYxf8AYno1mr","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All oracle conditions pass. Here's what I did:\n\n1. **Diagnosed the root cause**: The StatefulSet only mounts the `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret for file realm auth, but `report-user` was only present in the separate `user-provided-file-realm` secret.\n\n2. **Merged users into the aggregate secret**: Patched `es-file-realm-aggregate` to include `report-user`'s bcrypt hash in `users` and the `read:report-user` mapping in `users_roles`.\n\n3. **Restarted the StatefulSet** (rolling): Kubernetes `subPath` volume mounts don't live-update when secrets change, so a `rollout restart` was needed to put the new files on disk in the pods.\n\n4. **Defined the `read` role**: The `report-user` was assigned a role named `read`, but no such role existed (the `roles.yml` was empty). Created a native role named `read` via the Elasticsearch security API granting `read` index privilege on all indices — Elasticsearch resolves role privileges from both file and native sources by name.\n\nResult: `ops-user` still works (cluster status green), and `report-user` can now authenticate and read index data."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":839,"cache_read_input_tokens":50718,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":839},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1f65fe4f-c207-4ded-b85e-3b3711f38e9c","uuid":"4110ea89-07cc-44a9-a203-475f36572c40","request_id":"req_011Cc4ANQ1D7iwRiWJBuUpG2"}
